All that is known ol this letter is contained in Gascoigne, who (pp. 212-13) mentions twice over that the Lord Mayor, on reading it, and detecting in it very suspicions passages, tending to change of fidelity (for I interpret ‘fides' here to mean loyalty to the king) and of insurrection in the realm os England, sent it on to the king, and that when the king and lords read, it, they detected the same ten- dencies‚ and that great scandal arose about the great lords in the realm, who, he said in his letter, were on the side ol him and his English books. And he observes that all the temporal lords os the realm‚ who were with Henry, demanded that he should be expelled from the king's council and that os the lords. This expulsion took place about St. Martin’s day (Nov.11),1457,s0r no temporal lord in the king’s council would state his opinion and advice, or utter what he thought would be lor the good of the kingdom until Pecok was driven out ol the council chamber. Then Pecok was ordered to bring his books, nine in number, to the archbishop, in order that they might be examined by such doctors as the archbishop might appoint.

Pecok was degraded‚ his books burnt at Paul's Cross, where, Gascoigne says, the populace would have burnt him too ir they could have got at him, on Dec. 4. The same ceremony was performed at Carsax in Oxlord, by Chandler, Chancellor os the University and War- denos New College, on Dec. 17. He had made his abjuration on Nov. 28 at Lambeth‚ in the presence ol the Archbishop os Canterbury‚ the other bishops‚ and many doctors of theology, two temporal lords, Lords Stanley and De Scales, and many Knights. He was then committed to Maidstone to await judgment. Pecok, we are informed, was ultimately sent to the Monastery of Thorney, where a decent allowance was made him, but where he was not to be allowed writing materials.
